1 (e) “Forensic genetic genealogical DNA analysis and search” or “FGGS” means:
2 (1) the forensic genetic genealogical DNA analysis of biological material
3 using SNP or other sequencing techniques to develop an FGG profile;
4 (2) a subsequent search using the FGG profile in a publicly available
5 open–data personal genomics database or a direct–to–consumer genetic genealogy service
6 to find individuals related to the source of the FGG profile; and
7 (3) a genealogical search using public records and other lawful means to
8 obtain information in accordance with this title.
9 17–102.
10 (a) (1) FGGS may not be initiated without judicial authorization and without
11 certifying before the court that the forensic sample and the criminal case satisfy the criteria
12 set forth in this section.
13 (2) If an FGGS is certified before a court in accordance with this section,
14 the court shall authorize the initiation of the FGGS.
15 (b) A sworn affidavit shall be submitted by a law enforcement agent with approval
16 of a prosecutor from the relevant jurisdiction asserting that:
17 (1) THE IDENTITY OF THE PERPETRATOR IS UNKNOWN;
18 [(1)] (2) the crime is the commission of, or the attempt to commit, murder,
19 rape, a felony sexual offense, or a criminal act involving circumstances presenting a
20 substantial and ongoing threat to public safety or national security;
21 [(2)] (3) the forensic sample to be subjected to the FGGS is biological
22 material reasonably believed by investigators to have been deposited by a putative
23 perpetrator and that the forensic sample was collected from:
24 (i) a crime scene;
25 (ii) a person, an item, or a location connected to the criminal event;
26 or
27 (iii) the unidentified human remains of a suspected homicide victim;
28 AND
29 [(3)] (4) an STR DNA profile has already been developed from the forensic
30 sample, was entered into the statewide DNA database system and the national DNA
31 database system, and failed to identify a known individual[; and

